### If-Else in Go

`if-else` statements allow branching execution.

### Basic if-else

```go
if temperature > 30 {
    fmt.Println("Hot day")
} else {
    fmt.Println("Cool day")
}
```

### Nested if

```go
if x > 0 {
    if x > 100 {
        fmt.Println("Large positive")
    } else {
        fmt.Println("Small positive")
    }
} else if x < 0 {
    fmt.Println("Negative")
} else {
    fmt.Println("Zero")
}
```

### Short Statement Pattern

```go
if err := validate(input); err != nil {
    fmt.Println("Validation failed:", err)
    return
} else {
    fmt.Println("Input is valid")
}
```

### Common Patterns

```go
// Guard clause pattern
func process(x int) error {
    if x < 0 {
        return fmt.Errorf("negative value: %d", x)
    }
    // normal processing
    return nil
}

// Initialize and check
if file, err := os.Open("data.txt"); err == nil {
    defer file.Close()
    // use file
} else {
    fmt.Println("Cannot open:", err)
}
```

### Truthiness

Go has no truthiness - conditions must be boolean:

```go
// Correct:
if x > 0 { ... }

// Compile error:
// if x { ... }
// if 1 { ... }
```

> **Key Point:** Always prefer the guard clause pattern (early return) over deep nesting for error handling in Go.

codeExample:
package main

import (
    "fmt"
    "os"
)

func main() {
    args := os.Args[1:]

    if len(args) == 0 {
        fmt.Println("No arguments provided")
    } else if len(args) == 1 {
        fmt.Println("One argument:", args[0])
    } else {
        fmt.Printf("%d arguments: %v\n", len(args), args)
    }
}
